⚠️ Improvements (not mandatory, but HIGH value)
1. 🔥 Use management image (strongly recommended)
image: rabbitmq:3-management

👉 Why this matters:

You get UI at :15672
You can see queues, connections, failures

Without this:
👉 You’re debugging blind

2. 🔍 Expose management port
ports:
- name: amqp
  protocol: TCP
  port: 5672
  targetPort: 5672
- name: management
  protocol: TCP
  port: 15672
  targetPort: 15672
3. 🧠 Add resources (real production requirement)

RabbitMQ can eat memory under load.

resources:
  requests:
    cpu: 100m
    memory: 256Mi
  limits:
    cpu: 200m
    memory: 512Mi
4. ⚠️ Persistence (important if this was real prod)

Right now:
👉 If pod restarts → all queues gone

Real setup would need:

PVC (PersistentVolumeClaim)
5. 🧪 Health checks (optional but strong practice)

RabbitMQ doesn’t expose simple /health like HTTP apps, but you can still:

readinessProbe:
  tcpSocket:
    port: 5672
🧠 Real-world behavior you should expect

Even with this correct YAML:

👉 First few seconds:

Payment may fail connecting
RabbitMQ still starting

👉 Later:

Everything stabilizes
🔥 How you verify like a pro
kubectl get pods -n roboshop
kubectl get svc -n roboshop

Inside payment pod:

kubectl exec -it <payment-pod> -n roboshop -- sh

# test connection
nc -zv rabbitmq 5672
-----------------------
If you want next level 🚀
I’ll now break this setup like real production:

👉 RabbitMQ is UP
👉 Service works
👉 Still payment fails

And you’ll debug:

credentials
env injection
protocol mismatch

That’s where real expertise starts.